Foreign students and schools are bearing the losses

Restrictions on entry, third-country isolation, indefinite extension of the opening of school... new coronavirus epidemic, the return of Chinese New Year students face the problem of returning to school. Foreign students who need to return to school face different challenges, from Hubei's central cities, where traffic closures and restrictions have been imposed, to other provinces and cities where the epidemic is not severe. The problems associated with delayed return to school made them even more anxious.

AUSTRALIAN STUDENTS ADRIFT IN "Third Country"

After 12 days in Dubai, Lin Yan's room was upgraded from a standard room to a large suite with a living kitchen. It was an entirely unexpected journey -- as a result of the outbreak, she was barred from entering Australia for 14 days after being quarantined in a third country.

Lin Yan is an undergraduate student at the Australian National University. With the long summer holidays in the Southern Hemisphere, many Chinese students will choose to return to their hometown in the northern hemisphere for the Spring Festival. Linyan a holiday will be in Canberra Short rental apartment rented out, back to Hunan home. The original plan is to intern in the country, "think back can also save a rent. "

At first, she bought a ticket to Australia on January 21. However, the flight was cancelled due to departure from Wuhan. She then opted for a transfer to Singapore on February 1 and was told by the airline that Singapore restricted the entry of Chinese tourists. In a hurry to change the same day from Hong Kong flight, did not expect to be stopped before the check-in.

The reason for the delay was Australia's ban on entry into the country on February 1st, barring all visitors from mainland China except Australian citizens and permanent residents and their immediate family members.

"This policy is issued to carry out immediately, I saw the time has been in the airport. " Lin Yan can only admit to bad luck. The next day, at an official press conference, a spokesperson offered what appeared to be a compromise -- a declaration briefly posted on the Department of Health's website -- that Chinese tourists could enter a third country after 14 days. Since then, many stranded students have begun to return to school through "third-country isolation" . But, in fact, this method is not safe either.

There is really no energy to toss about. Lin Yan gave up most of the "curvy back-to-school" overseas students' Association's choice of Landing Visa Countries in Southeast Asia such as Thailand, and also did not choose relatively low-cost neighboring countries such as Russia and South Korea, it's the United Arab Emirates.

"It's mainly a visa issue. Thailand has only 15 days on arrival. I'm worried that Australia's policy has changed and 15 days are not enough. I can't wait for South Korea to apply for a visa ahead of time. Let's choose a safer country. " According to the visa rules of the United Arab Emirates, chinese passport holders who stay in the United Arab Emirates for up to 30 days for short-term reasons such as travel, business, family visits and transit may enjoy visa-free access.

"I only wanted to go back to school smoothly, but I didn't expect to buy all my usual one-year air tickets within a month. " Apart from the soaring ticket prices and the extra travel costs of "living in" a third country for up to half a month, lin Yan's apartment in Canberra has been vacant for a month and she still has to pay high rents. "I wanted to save money, but I spent more. "

Until now, Lim's earlier purchase of a singapore-to-sydney flight may have ended up costing her tens of thousands of dollars when Singapore Airlines refused to give her a refund. And this trip had to the UAE half-month tour, Linyan even accidentally got to know the same choice in the UAE "isolation" alumni. She realized that in order to return to school and in a third country floating half a month of foreign students are definitely not a minority.

Lin Yan's tortuous experience is just a microcosm. Among the group of Chinese students who want to return to school normally, Australian students are more affected by the outbreak. After the domestic outbreak was declared a public health emergency by the World Health Organization (WHO) , the Australian side of a series of changes in policy, let them feel helpless.

Officials have said no timetable has been set for extending the ban, depending on the circumstances of the outbreak. On February 20th Australia extended its travel ban by another week, on top of an earlier one-week extension.

At present, "14-day isolation in a third country" , as an incompletely clear but the only feasible way, has become the first choice of most students staying in the country. Some travel agencies have even launched the "14-day, 13-night" travel package, with a more favorable price arrangements for foreign students in the third country "drift. ".

"I just want to go back to school, " wrote many overseas students waiting to enter Australia in "quarantine" third countries under the related Weibo topic.

Within the walls of the city

Most students from outside Hubei can still find ways to "curvy back to school" without being completely barred from the country, but the future of those stranded in Hubei remains uncertain.

Ogaya, a RMIT University prep student, has been in quarantine in Wuhan for 28 days. Originally scheduled for February 3, due to the third country isolation time problem, the school specially adjusted the school time for Chinese students, has been postponed to March 2.

But students like Ogaya in Wuhan don't even have the chance to be isolated in a third country. She does not know when Wuhan will be able to resume traffic. "If we don't get to school by March 2, the school will suspend us for six months to a year. " Like most international students, she rents a house in Australia, the monthly rent plus utilities costs more than 10,000 yuan. If we continue to wait indefinitely, the various expenses in Australia will be wasted like water, making it difficult for the relatively ordinary overseas students to afford.

Tongzi, a British student, has been absent from school for a month. Every day she spent at home made her more anxious. "All the students in the country who can't go back to school have online classes, " she quipped. "We have nothing but to contact the school and despair over and over again. " At her school, only big classes like math and calculus have videos, most core professional courses do not offer online instruction. Even the big class recording screen teaching, "can only see the teacher's PPT, can not see the teacher to write the calculation process. ".

"I really don't want to repeat a grade. " Tong Son Countless Times with friends complain.

There are also people who have been anxious for days and have finally seen a glimmer of light. On February 19, Wuhan Native Nan Zhi, who is facing a graduation project problem in Sweden, received an email from her alma mater offering to help her extend the deadline for her graduation project indefinitely.

She was due to return to school on February 10, and she has been anxious about her graduation project for almost a month since the city was shut down. "My graduation project has been contracted with a Japanese University, and schools in Sweden and Japan have provided financial support. If I can not return to school, not only will my graduation be affected, but there will also be problems in the implementation of the contract, there may be legal disputes and personal reputation will be damaged. "

She has been in constant communication with the school for nearly a month, but it has been difficult for the school to give a definite answer as she has not been able to tell when she will return to school. Therefore, when the school told "can be indefinitely delayed, as long as you ensure good health" email, south gardenia suspended for a month's heart finally gently fall to the ground.

However, not all schools can make such a commitment. Xiang Zhang, a Canadian student also facing graduation, was overwhelmed by the visa issue. Xiang Zhang's student visa expired at the end of March, "I was going to come back for the New Year and apply for a work visa on January 29. If you can't get back to Canada before your visa expires, you need to re-apply for a new visa at home, with a process that takes at least three months."

Most let him heartache is, years ago in Canada to settle down the job, because can not arrive at the post has been foiled. "I lost my job, I'm still paying rent, I'm making $1,500 a month, and I have a lot of things I can't deal with, " Xiang Zhang said, recalling the mess he faced before graduation.

The application is not pessimistic

Since the outbreak, IELTS has been the first to cancel tests in mainland China from January to March this year, and toefl and Gre Exams in mainland China in February. For students preparing to go abroad, the repeated cancellation of exams is likely to have a direct impact on their study plans.

In contrast, the public sent to study abroad, the extension of the measures more secure. According to a report by Xinhua News Agency, the Management Committee of the State Study Abroad Fund said that for students who are officially sent by the state to study abroad before June 30,2020, if they can not be sent as originally planned because of the epidemic, if it is necessary to apply for extension of assignment, change the unit or country of study abroad, or give up the qualification of studying abroad on public assignment, it shall be supported. Those who apply for renouncing the qualification of studying abroad on public assignment due to epidemic situation shall not be subject to the restriction that they can not apply for studying abroad on state public assignment within two years.

So far, however, no foreign universities have said they will not accept new students from China's "epidemic areas" this summer. Even so, many people are still concerned about whether the continued suspension of visas and cancellation of flights in many countries because of the new pneumonia outbreak will indirectly affect Chinese citizens'plans to study abroad?

Shu Yuan, a senior consultant at a study abroad agency, told China News weekly that based on experience after the SARS epidemic 17 years ago, the impact on studying abroad would not be significant. "while the number of Chinese students was much smaller then, the UK, the US, Australia and Canada, the major overseas countries, are not much different in terms of recruiting students to the Chinese region. "

The main reason for the limited enrollment is that students who are applying to study abroad at this time can not complete their application until the next year. "The impact of the epidemic on studying abroad next year is not so pessimistic, " said Shu.

As for a question that many netizens are concerned about: Are Hubei students likely to be discriminated against or even rejected in the process of applying to schools? Shuyuan assured him that he would not. "In fact, with reference to the situation during SARS, many questions will be answered, provided that the epidemic can be brought under control as soon as possible. "

But it is not just the international student community that is worried about the uncertainty of a large number of Chinese students entering the country. According to the Guardian, a lecturer at the University of Sydney has said that the number of part-time teachers employed depends on the number of students enrolled, and that the number of part-time teachers will be reduced if students cancel classes. If the ban is extended again and again, students who pay high tuition fees will have to take online classes from home, which will indirectly affect next year's enrollment.

Both foreign students and the university are trying to avoid a series of negative effects brought by the epidemic. But they all knew that the solution to all the problems lay in containment, and that spring was coming.
